                <affiliation>The Century</affiliation>
                <note>Robert Underwood Johnson, born in 1853, was an editor of The Century
                    Magazine from 1879 until 1913. He also served as the American Ambassador to
                    Italy from 1920-1921, and was a founding member of the American Copyright
                    League. He was a published poet, and active in a number of humanitarian and
                    artistic pursuits (Kit Messick, "Biographical Note," <hi rend="italic">Robert
                        Underwood Johnson Papers 1875-1937 Finding Aid</hi>, The New York Public
                    Library, Humanities and Social Sciences Library, Manuscripts and Archives
                    Division, 2008: v).</note>
            </person>
        </listPerson>

        <listObject>
            <object type="book">
                <objectIdentifier xml:id="trc">
                    <msName>The Rainbow Chasers</msName>
                </objectIdentifier>
                <note>The book "The Rainbow Chasers" is Chesnutt's attempt at entering the popular
                    market with a nonracial romance. The conventional story centers on a
                    well-meaning, middle-aged bachelor who acts as a go-between for suitors to a
                    beautiful widow, who marries the bachelor in the end. Ultimately, Chesnutt is
                    unable to find a publisher for this book. (William L. Andrews, <hi rend="italic"
                        >The Literary Career of Charles W. Chesnutt</hi>, Louisiana State University
                    Press, 1999: 121-2).</note>
                <note n="1">Chesnutt met with Johnson in New York City on March 24th. On that day,
                    he received a letter from Houghton, Mifflin, rejecting his story, "The Rainbow
                    Chasers." In response, Chesnutt began searching for a new publisher. Johnson
                    declined this manuscript on May 2nd, for not having "the qualities necessary for
                    availability as a serial for <hi rend="italic">The Century</hi>, though it has
                    striking good features for a book" (Charles W. Chesnutt, <hi rend="italic">“To
                        Be an Author”: Letters of Charles W. Chesnutt, 1889-1905</hi>, ed. Joseph R.
                    McElrath, Jr. and Robert C. Leitz, III, Princeton University Press, 1997:
                    145-6).</note>
            </object>

            <object type="magazine">
                <objectIdentifier xml:id="tc">
                    <msName>The Century</msName>
                </objectIdentifier>
                <note><hi rend="italic">The Century Magazine</hi> was an American magazine
                    published by The Century Company that replaced <hi rend="italic">Scribner's
                        Monthly Magazine</hi> in 1881. The magazine published illustrated articles
                    on history, science, and literature, sometimes publishing fiction as well. In
                    1930, it merged with <hi rend="italic">The Forum</hi>.</note>
            </object>
        </listObject>

